ce:section.ce:para:
To assess the practicality of N, S-CQDs/AgNCs, actual water samples were used to detect Hg²⁺. Three distinct water samples, comprising tap water, lake water, and river water, were supplemented with varying levels of Hg²⁺ (0, 1, 3, and 5 µM). The average recoveries ranged from 94.20 % to 102.40 %, with a relative standard deviation (RSD) of less than 4.75 % ( Table 2), proving that the prepared probe achieves good precision and high reliability. To re-verify the reliability of fluorescence detection of Hg²⁺, the cold vapor atomic absorption spectroscopy (CVAAS) was used to test Hg²⁺ according to National Environmental Protection Standard of the People's Republic of China (HJ 597–2011), compare with the results of N, S-CQDs/AgNCs. As shown in Fig. S3, the linear range of the CVAAS calibration curve was 1–10 μg/L, and the equation was y = 14.3804 ×[Hg
2+
]+ 7.7910 (R²=0.9980). In Table 2, the average recoveries ranged from 91.12 % to 104.41 % with the relative standard deviation (RSD) less than 4.86 %. The comparative data between the fluorescence probe and the CVAAS show excellent applicability. Response to Student’s t-test evaluation: A Student’s t-test (α=0.05, degrees of freedom=8) was performed on 9 real-sample datasets obtained from both methods. The calculated t-value (0.01273) was significantly lower than the critical t-value (2.306), confirming no statistically significant difference between the fluorescence probe and CVAAS, revealing a strong correlation.
